# Ansible for Site Reliability Engineering (SRE)

This section explains Ansible from beginner to advanced level, aligned with how a **Senior SRE actually uses it in production environments**.

---

## Why Ansible Matters in SRE

Ansible is one of the most important tools for:

* Infrastructure automation
* Configuration management
* Server provisioning
* Incident response automation
* Platform standardization
* Large-scale fleet management

A Senior SRE uses Ansible to ensure:

* Systems are reproducible
* Deployments are consistent
* Configuration drift is eliminated
* Infrastructure is recoverable

---

# 1. What Ansible Is

Ansible is an **agentless automation tool** that uses SSH to manage remote systems.

## Architecture

```text
Control Node (Ansible installed)
        |
        | SSH
        v
Managed Nodes (Servers)
```

Ansible executes tasks using:

* Modules
* Playbooks
* Inventory files

---

# 2. Ansible Core Concepts

## Inventory

Defines the systems Ansible will manage.

### Default location

```bash
/etc/ansible/hosts

sudo mkdir -p /etc/ansible/hosts
```

### Example

```
[webservers]
10.0.0.10
10.0.0.11

[dbservers]
10.0.0.20
10.0.0.21
```

### IP range

```ini
10.0.0.[10:20]
```

Note:


### Check inventory


ansible-inventory --list

ubuntu@ansible-control:~$ ansible-inventory --list
{
    "_meta": {
        "hostvars": {}
    },
    "all": {
        "children": [
            "servers",
            "ungrouped"
        ]
    },
    "servers": {
        "hosts": [
            "192.168.1.100",
            "192.168.1.101"
        ]
    }
}
ubuntu@ansible-control:~$ 

Test it:

ansible all -m ping

If it fails, check and troubleshoot the hosts:

nc -vz 192.168.1.101 22
telnet 192.168.1.101 22
sudo systemctl status ssh
